{
  "text": "A core area of research on NFC concerns its influence on attitude development and change. According to the ELM [CITATION_1] ) people who are motivated and able to engage in laborious information processing activities, are more likely to develop accurate and unbiased representations of the (social) world (central processing route). People who lack cognitive motivation engage in heuristic information processing and are more susceptible to judgmental biases (peripheral processing route). Recent literature extended the role of cognitive motivation (NFC) from persuasion to social cognition and shows that low NFC is an important precursor of social attitudes like acceptance of stereotyping [CITATION_2] and racism [CITATION_3] . In social-cognitive terms, stereotypes are peripheral cues that influence social perception [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Stereotyping oversimplifies social information related to outgroups and favors (negative) prejudicial judgments toward the members of the out-groups. [CITATION_6] argue that exposure to social stereotypes influence the cognitive processes of people scoring high in NFC in different ways than the ones of those scoring low in NFC. Although, motivated social perceivers (people scoring high in NFC) have an enhanced recollection of stereotype-consistent information their social judgments seem to be less prejudicial when compared to those of non-motivated social-perceivers (people scoring low in NFC) [CITATION_7] .",
